    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-12T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-12T17:00:00-05:00" n="328"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/315</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-12T23:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 12, 1918, 11 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received</hi> (<hi rend="italic">April 13</hi>),
                            <hi rend="italic">4.32 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9475. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 416. My No. 408. Swedes very anxious to change programme mentioned by having
                    the boats leave Sweden in ballast direct for Plate; other conditions remain the
                    same. Foreign Office thinks it very desirable to grant this concession for
                    political reasons; do you agree? Please cable reply, urgent. The main inducement
                    for Sweden to come to a definite agreement with us is owing to the great
                    shortage of cereals, the lack of which is becoming more apparent in Sweden
                    daily, and any arrangements like the foregoing, which will show the Swedes that
                    there is a chance of getting grain quickly should an agreement be signed, I
                    think, are extremely advisable to make, outside the added advantage there is of
                    getting ships outside Swedish waters.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
